The Tariffs ledger, positive and negative, is far more complicated than established opinion (or nationalist enthusiasm) is allowing for. 
For the US specifically, the highest priority positive factor is this: 
Losing core strategic industrial capacity through international division of labor is a geopolitically unacceptable outcome of naively optimistic anti-mercantile liberalism. If it turns out you don't have comparative advantage in cutting-edge meta-machine-tools, you lose the world (and every type of true liberalism, naively cosmopolitan, or not, along with it). 
It's fine for Switzerland to specialize down to financial services and chocolate. For the USA, not so much.

... Lying back and waiting to find out what the 'world community' (through the global market) thinks your nation should be producing is not an acceptable position for the redoubt of liberty on earth. (It's mostly going to be cartoons and other things without sharp edges.)

... If cosmopolitan economic liberalism reaches the empirical conclusion that drone armadas are not efficiently produced within the territory of the continental United States, it falsifies itself through geostrategic self-contradiction.
Geopolitically-structured trade diplomacy, involving carefully-balanced tarrifs, should carry the burden of industrial policy without requiring big government.
... Vastly easier said than done, of course. Truly epic political-economic experiment in process.
... But playing cosmopolitan laissez-faire economic liberalism while your competitors are playing hard-power global domination is over.
China is in very many ways an extremely impressive country. You don't get to (successfully) play planetary destiny with them on easy mode.
Yes, saw that. Impressive.

All manufacturing isn't equal. Garden furniture and cigarette lighters you can lose. Machine tools and cutting-edge electronics not so much. 
The special strategic value of upstream industrialism is poorly recognized by consumer signals.
